'''John Sigvard Olsen''' (November 6, 1892 &ndash; January 26, 1963) was an American [[vaudeville|vaudevillian]] and comedian.

==Biography==
John Sigvard Olsen was born in [[Peru, Indiana]] on November 6, 1892, the son of a [[Norwegians|Norwegian]] immigrant, Gustav Olsen, a boiler-maker for the railroad, and his wife, Catherine, who was of [[German-speaking Switzerland|Swiss-German]] descent. He graduated from [[Northwestern University]] in 1912 with a degree in music and hit the Vaudeville circuit. In 1914 he met [[Chic Johnson]], who was advertising himself as the "Greatest Ragtime Pianist in the Midwest".{{cn|date=August 2015}}

The two performers met when they were hired as musicians in the same band. When the band broke up "Ole" Olsen and "Chic" Johnson formed the [[Olsen and Johnson]] comedy team. They really did not have a set act but found themselves booked into a small Chicago nightclub as part of ''Mike Fritzol's Frolics''. 

When it came time for their turn in the show, unannounced and not particularly welcome, the duo pushed a piano onstage. Johnson seated himself at the keyboard and began to plunk out a ragtime tune. Olsen joined in with his violin and started singing, making up comical lyrics as he went along. The pair began to exchange "[[patter]]", mostly insults, and the soon-to-be-famous "Olsen and Johnson" team emerged. They performed in Vaudeville, as well as making some film appearances, for 24 years before hitting [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] in 1938 with the show ''[[Hellzapoppin' (film)|Hellzapoppin']]'', later successfully filmed.{{cn|date=August 2015}}

Ole Olsen was married twice. He had three children with his first wife, Lillian: J. C., Joy, and [[Moya Lear|Moya]]. They were later divorced. His son, J. C., committed suicide. Moya married [[Bill Lear|William P. Lear]] of [[Learjet]] fame in 1942. Ole was involved in a serious automobile accident in 1950 and recuperated at the Lear home. In June 1961 Ole married Eileen Maria Osthoff, a dancer and choreographer he had known for eight years.

Ole's ambition was to make people laugh. He is remembered for the quote, "May you live as long as you laugh, and laugh as long as you live", which are cited on his headstone {{Citation needed|date=February 2015}}. Olsen died in [[Albuquerque, New Mexico]] at the age of 70 of a kidney ailment, and is interred in Palm Desert Memorial in [[Las Vegas, Nevada]], in a grave adjoining that of Chic Johnson.{{cn|date=August 2015}}

